Yes, but handle them differently based on who calls them.

### `startAuthentication(...)`

This is browser-facing. You should catch unexpected errors and redirect to your UI error page, just like callback.

```java
@GetMapping("/start")
public ResponseEntity<Void> startAuthentication(
        @RequestHeader(value = "APP_ID", required = false) String headerAppId,
        @RequestParam(value = "appId", required = false) String queryAppId,
        HttpServletRequest request) {

    try {
        String appId = headerAppId != null && !headerAppId.isBlank()
                ? headerAppId
                : queryAppId;

        if (appId == null || appId.isBlank()) {
            return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.FOUND)
                    .location(URI.create("/arthur-core/error/technical"))
                    .build();
        }

        HttpSession session = request.getSession(true);

        String pendingRedirect =
                (String) session.getAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_REDIRECT");
        Long pendingTime =
                (Long) session.getAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_TIME");

        if (pendingRedirect != null && pendingTime != null) {
            long age = System.currentTimeMillis() - pendingTime;

            if (age < 10_000) {
                return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.FOUND)
                        .location(URI.create(pendingRedirect))
                        .build();
            }
        }

        String redirectUrl = authService.startAuthentication(appId);

        session.setAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_REDIRECT", redirectUrl);
        session.setAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_TIME", System.currentTimeMillis());

        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.FOUND)
                .location(URI.create(redirectUrl))
                .build();

    } catch (Exception exception) {
        log.error("Authentication start failed", exception);

        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.FOUND)
                .location(URI.create("/arthur-core/error/technical"))
                .build();
    }
}
```

Do not expose technical exception messages to the browser here.

### `exchange(...)`

Do **not** redirect this one. It is a backend-to-backend JSON API called by B2Boost. B2Boost needs an HTTP error response, not an HTML page.

Keep it simple:

```java
@PostMapping("/handoff/exchange")
public ResponseEntity<HandoffExchangeResponse> exchange(
        @RequestBody HandoffExchangeRequest request) {

    if (request == null || request.getCode() == null
            || request.getCode().isBlank()) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Handoff code must not be blank");
    }

    return ResponseEntity.ok(handoffService.exchange(request.getCode()));
}
```

Then handle handoff exceptions in your existing API exception handler, returning JSON. For example:

```java
@ExceptionHandler(TechnicalException.class)
public ResponseEntity<Map<String, Object>> handleTechnicalException(
        TechnicalException exception) {

    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST)
            .body(Map.of(
                    "status", HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST.value(),
                    "error", "HANDOFF_EXCHANGE_FAILED",
                    "message", exception.getMessage()
            ));
}
```

For expired/used/invalid handoff code, `400 Bad Request` is acceptable for now. Later you may distinguish:

* `400` invalid or expired code
* `409` already-used code
* `503` Redis or Arthur infrastructure failure

